,"1070–Female":"1070–Deceased","about 1140":"about 1140","1238":"1238","1126":"1126","1115":"1115","ABT 1100":"about 1100","1100":"1100","15 February 1126":"15 February 1126","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","AFT 1162":"after 1162","1062":"1062","1070":"1070","of,Arnstedt,Halle,Germany":"Arnstedt, Mansfelder Gebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany","Arnstadt, Schwarzburg-Sonderhausen, Thuringia":"Arnstadt, Schwarzburg-Sondershausen, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"von","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Walter","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, superseding the native Old English form, <i>Wealdhere</i>. It was a very popular name in medieval England, normally pronounced ‘Water’."],"variants":[{"name":"Walther","meanings":["from <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i> ‘army’; name of the famous medieval minnesinger  Walther von der Vogelweide  (  <i>c.</i>1170– <i>c.</i>1230 )."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Graf Walter II von Arnstedt was born about 1100, in Arnstedt, Mansfelder Gebirgskreis, Saxony, Germany, his father, Count Walther von Arnstein, was 40 and his mother, Mrs Walther von Arnstedt, was 32. He had at least 1 son with Ermengard von Plötzkau. He died after 1162."},"et":{"ABT 1100–AFT 1162":"umbes 1100–pärast 1162","1100–1162":"1100–1162","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1140–1238":"1140–1238","1062–1126":"1062–1126","1070–Female":"1070–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1238":"1238","1126":"1126","1115":"1115","ABT 1100":"umbes 1100","1100":"1100","15 February 1126":"15. veebruar 1126","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","AFT 1162":"pärast 1162","1062":"1062","1070":"1070","of,Arnstedt,Halle,Germany":"Arnstedt, Mansfelder Gebirgskreis, Sachsen, Saksamaa","Arnstadt, Schwarzburg-Sonderhausen, Thuringia":"Arnstadt, Schwarzburg-Sondershausen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"ABT 1100–AFT 1162":"noin 1100–